We follow a feature-branch workflow. Developers create feature branches from the main development branch, raise pull requests for peer review, and merge changes after approval. For production releases, we use release branches, and urgent production fixes are handled through hotfix branches. This approach helps maintain code quality, supports CI/CD pipelines, and enables controlled deployments.

5)	"How do you resolve merge conflicts?"

When a merge conflict occurs, I first identify the conflicting files using git status. Then, I open the files and manually review the conflict markers (<<<<<<<, =======, >>>>>>>). After deciding which changes to keep or combining both changes, I remove the conflict markers, save the files, and stage them using git add. Finally, I complete the merge with git commit. I also run tests to ensure everything works correctly before pushing the changes.
        ……………………………………………………………………………………………………………………………
If two developers modify the same lines in a file, Git cannot automatically decide which version to keep. In that case, I discuss the changes with the team if needed, merge the required code manually, test the application, and then complete the merge.

6)	"What is the difference between git pull and fetch?"

Git Fetch
git fetch origin
•	Downloads the latest changes from the remote repository. 
•	Does not merge them into your current branch. 
Git Pull
git pull origin main
•	Downloads the latest changes. 
•	Automatically merges them into your current branch.

